at the exact opposite is true: that we habitually use digital technologies to re-embed ourselves within urban environments. The Digital City advocates for the need to rethink our everyday interactions with digital infrastructures, navigation technologies, and social media as we move through the world. Drawing on five case studies from global and mid-sized cities to illustrate the concept of “re-placeing,” Germaine R. Halegoua shows how different populations employ urban broadband networks, social and locative media platforms, digital navigation, smart cities, and creative placemaking initiatives to turn urban spaces into places with deep meanings and emotional attachments. Through timely narratives of everyday urban life, Halegoua argues that people use digital media to create a unique sense of place within rapidly changing urban environments and that a sense of place is integral to understanding contemporary relationships with digital media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCities and townsxTechnological innovations. 0aInternetxSocial aspects. 0aSmart cities. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aFoursquare.  aGPS.  aGoogle Fiber.  aInstagram.  aKansas City.  aNational Endowment for the Arts.  aPortugal.  aSouth Korea.  aUnited Arab Emirates.  abroadband networks.  acognitive mapping.  acreative placemaking projects.  acreative placemaking.  adigital connection.  adigital connectivity.  adigital environments.  adigital inclusion.  adigital infrastructure.  adigital maps.  adigital media technology.  adigital media use.  adigital media.  adigital storytelling.  adigital technology.  afunding for digital initiatives.  afunding practices.  ageo-location.  ainstitutional support.  alocation-based social media.  alocative media.  amobile navigation.